article.headline: Thibault becomes Sun's winningest coach
article.linkText: Sun pull away from Monarchs with strong second half
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 15 points
and 14 rebounds, Nykesha Sales added 14 points and the Connecticut
Sun pulled away in the second half Friday night for a 61-50 victory
over the Sacramento Monarchs.

Connecticut coach Mike Thibault, who became the winningest coach
in franchise history with his 45th career victory, will miss the
team's game in Phoenix on Saturday night to attend his mother's
funeral in Saratoga, Calif.

Patricia Thibault died Wednesday at age 78.

"My mom was really hoping to be at this game, so emotionally I
just couldn't get that out of my mind all night," Thibault said.

"I'll be at the funeral Monday and be home for our game Tuesday
(against Sacramento)," he said.

Margo Dydek had nine points and Lindsay Whalen and Asjha Jones
each had eight for the Sun (9-2), who have won eight of nine games.

"We feel like our team is a family, and anytime a family member
has something like this happen in their lives you rally around
them," Lindsay Whalen said. "So that's what we did, we rallied
around coach."

In the battle between the league's conference leaders, the Sun
overcame an 11-point deficit, using a 25-4 run to assume a 55-45
lead with 4:04 remaining.

Despite playing with a sprained right knee she suffered
Wednesday in practice, DeMya Walker had 16 points and six rebounds
for Sacramento (8-3), which had its three-game winning streak
snapped.

Yolanda Griffith of Sacramento had a sub-par game with six
points and nine rebounds. But she made a free throw with 12:06 left
in the opening half, becoming the eighth player in WNBA history to
reach 3,000 career points.

Nicole Powell had her worst game of the year for Sacramento,
which was held to a season-low 50 points. She missed all 10
field-goal attempts and scored one point. She entered the game
averaging 12.2 points.

"It was our worst performance ever," Powell said. "Bottom
line: It was not pretty."

Walker scored 12 first-half points for the Monarchs, who led
31-28 at the break.
